<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-03-16T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-03-16T09:00:00-05:00" n="575" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d575">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">723.2515/3299: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Culbertson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Santiago</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-03-16T10:00:00-04:00">March 16, 1929—10
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 12:25 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>41. With reference to paragraph 4 in your 29, March 15, 3 p.m., remind
                            Cady that all the ports of Peru and Chile north of Valparaiso including
                            the present Arica any [<hi rend="italic">are</hi>?] lighterage ports. I
                            have assumed that the port either at San José or Escritos would be of
                            the same character.</p>
                        <p>Copy furnished Lima.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Culbertson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>